<FIRST>r i BC-EastBloc-Dates     12-22 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-East Bloc-Dates,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>East European Key Dates</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Romania Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some key dates for change in Eastern Europe this year:
   AUG. 18-19 _ Poland's leader, Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski,
announces the first non-Communist government in POLAND since World
War II, nominating Solidarity activist Tadeusz Mazowiecki as prime
minister after Solidarity swept June elections.
   OCT. 7 _ The Communist Party in HUNGARY formally disbands,
reconstituting itself as Hungarian Socialist Party. Parliament
rewrites the constitution and adopts laws allowing several parties
to contest free elections next year.
   NOV. 9 _ EAST GERMANY lifts travel restrictions and opens
gateways through Berlin Wall three weeks after resignation of
Communist Party chief Erich Honecker, who supervised the building
of the wall in 1961. Honecker's hand-picked replacement Egon Krenz
and the ruling party Politburo resigns a month later after
Parliament voted to eliminate the party's constitutionally
guaranteed hold on power.
   NOV. 10 _ Communist Party chief Todor Zhivkov of BULGARIA is
ousted and replaced by a moderate.
   NOV. 29 _ In CZECHOSLOVAKIA, Parliament deletes the leading role
of the Communist Party from the constitution after massive protests
force the resignations of hard-line party chief Milos Jakes and the
Politburo.
   DEC. 22 _ President Nicolae Ceausescu of ROMANIA, the last
hard-line ruler in the Soviet bloc, is overthrown by a week-long
popular revolt during which hundreds of demonstrators were killed
by security forces.
</TEXT>
