<FIRST>r f PM-GiftCertificateFraud Bjt   12-22 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gift Certificate Fraud, Bjt,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gift Certificate Fraud Popular During Holiday Season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talented con artists won't be stopping at
forged checks and stolen credit cards this holiday season,
retailers and security experts say. Gift certificates have become a
hot new tool of the trade.
   ``The economic criminals are getting away from buying hard
merchandise and they're buying gift certificates,'' said Jack
Scott, director of loss prevention for JBS Associates of Ringwood,
one of the country's largest check guarantee companies.
   ``They realize it's a weakness in the merchants' system,'' he
said.
   The thieves use stolen credit cards or bogus checks to buy the
certificates because they are more difficult to trace, more
flexible and can be resold.
   ``Once they get the gift certificate it's like money in their
pocket,'' said Ray Watson, a loss prevention detective for Sears,
Roebuck and Co. Inc.
   Some certificates are redeemed for merchandise, which also can
later be resold. Thieves may also buy an item with the certificate
and later take it back, asking for a cash refund.
   Scott, whose company guarantees the credit-worthiness of checks
for merchants, estimates the going rate for gift certificates on
the street is 70 to 75 cents on the dollar compared to 35 cents on
the dollar for merchandise.
   In one case, Scott said, a con artist was able to pass more than
$50,000 in counterfeit gift certificates in less than two weeks
before he was caught.
   Gift certificates are easy targets because few merchants keep
track of them by serializing them or recording numbers of documents
that have been redeemed, he said. Gift certificate purchases are
often rung up as cash, making it difficult to later trace them.
   In addition, they often are printed on regular paper instead of
on paper with watermarks or other means of preventing reproduction
by increasingly sophisticated laser copiers, he said.
   Lewis Shealy, vice president of loss prevention for the
Chicago-based Marshall Fields department stores, said his company's
25 stores had gift-certificate losses of about $10,000 last year
even though they serialized their certificates.
   ``They were using photocopy machines to counterfeit them and
they looked very, very good,'' he said. ``During a busy Christmas
season your chances of passing them are 100 percent.''
   This year, the store hired a company that designs federal bank
notes to create a system under which the word ``void'' appears on
photocopies of gift certificates, he said.
   Officials from federal and state agencies and the National
Retail Merchants Association said they had no figures on gift
certificate fraud.
   ``That's not an area we've been called into at all,'' said
association spokesman John Gary.
   Richard Adams, a spokesman for the U.S. Secret Service in
Washington, D.C., said the agency does not keep statistics to
distinguish certificate fraud from other fraud like credit card
misuse.
   Scott estimated the use of stolen checks or credit cards to buy
gift certificates is up by about 20 percent this year.
   Scott said the extent of the problem was brought home to him
this summer through interviews with the arrested heads of a
national ring estimated to have cashed more than $35 million worth
of stolen checks in the last three years.
   ``They predicted there is going to be a major loss to retailers
this holiday season because of the popularity of gift certificate
fraud among economic criminals,'' Scott said.
   Not all stores are victims of gift certificate fraud.
   ``I don't have any known fraud in my gift certificate areas,''
said Ed Barclay, director of loss prevention for Saks Fifth
Avenue's 46 stores, which serialize their certificates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891222-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-89 0138EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Panama-Sanctions Bjt   12-22 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Sanctions, Bjt,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lifting U.S. Sanctions Should Benefit Panama's Sickly Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. government attorneys are hard at work on a plan to free
about $375 million in Panamanian assets held in the United States,
a move that is sure to be a big boost for Panama's ailing economy.
   A spokesman for the Treasury Department said Thursday he did not
know when a plan would be completed that would unblock Panamanian
bank accounts and allow the Latin American country to collect back
taxes from the U.S. corporations that operate there.
   President Bush called for the ``orderly unblocking of Panamanian
government assets'' held in the United States after the swearing-in
of the democratically elected Guillermo Endara as president earlier
this week.
   The sanctions were imposed by the Reagan administration to
pressure Gen. Manuel Noriega, the Panamanian dictator who has been
indicted in the United States on drug trafficking charges.
   The United States cut off all military and economic aid in July
1987. Further sanctions sharply restricted U.S. companies that do
business in Panama, froze Panamanian assets held in the United
States, held payments relating to operating the Panama Canal in
escrow and forbade American companies from paying taxes and fees to
the Noriega regime.
   Companies were allowed either to put money due the Panamanian
government into escrow accounts overseen by the Federal Reserve
Bank or establish reserve accounts on their own books.
   The Treasury spokesman said the government must develop a plan
that ensures ``the assets go to the legitimate goverment'' and that
U.S. residents and corporations that made escrow payments to cover
fees and taxes owed to Panama be given proper credit.
   An official of a large U.S. company operating in Panama,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said, ``There has been no
signal at this point from the administration as to those taxes
going to this particular government.''
   Economists have estimated that the sanctions cost Panama about
$225 million last year, when the nation's gross domestic product
fell 17 percent.
   For Panama, gaining access to $375 million will mark the first
step in getting its economy in order.
   ``It's not big money to us, but it's certainly big money to
them,'' said Robert Brusca, chief economist at Nikko Securities Co.
International Inc.
   As relations warm, U.S. banks will be more inclined to lend to
Panama, where loan availability has been off sharply.
   ``Noriega's access to the U.S. banking system ... was being
impeded to the greatest extent that we could, and it's very hard to
run a modern economy that way,'' Brusca said.
   Panama owes the rest of the world about $5.3 billion. Though the
figure pales in comparison to other developing countries, it is
extremely high on a per-capita basis. Panama's debt equals about
$2,200 per capita while Brazil's debt is roughly $790 per capita,
according to figures provided by the World Bank.
   Panama first missed a payment to banks in mid-1987 and since has
faced increasing difficulties servicing its debt, said Luis R.
Luis, director of the Latin America department of the Institute for
International Finance.
   Luis said the money due Panama from the lifting of U.S.
sanctions ``could be used to pay back the arrears. It would be a
very good use of funds as far as banks are concerned.''
   Experts said the lifting of sanctions would certainly improve
Panamanian citizens' view of America.
   ``This can really help to pull more of the people onto the U.S.
side. If we can kick out the rat (Noriega) and lift sanctions, it
would improve the economic lot of a lot people,'' Brusca said.
   In addition to lifting sanctions, the U.S. government said it
would not proceed with an order, which would have gone into effect
at the end of January, barring ships bearing Panama's flag from
U.S. ports.
   It was unclear whether a ban on the import of Panamanian sugar
would be lifted, but experts said the amount is insignificant and
that sugar is a minor factor in Panama's economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891222-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-89 0140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FundsDisclosure     12-22 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Funds Disclosure,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Proposes Stiffer Disclosure Rules for Mutual Funds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission is
seeking public comment on proposed new rules that would require
mutual funds to simplify and expand the information they are
required to supply investors.
   The SEC agreed to submit the proposals to public scrutiny on
Thursday.
   One proposals seeks to clarify descriptions of funds to
investors, a second would provide better measures of fund
performance and a third would require disclosure of who is making
fund investment decisions.
   At least one of the proposals, requiring funds to identify those
managing their stock portfolios, is expected to meet with the
stiffest industry opposition, SEC staffers acknowledged.
   ``I would say the majority of the industry people that we've
heard from think it's a bad idea,'' said Kathryn McGrath of the SEC.
   Ms. McGrath, head of the SEC's Division of Investment
Management, conceded that previous attempts to implement a fund
manager disclosure rule were ``blown out of the water by a wave of
criticism.''
   The Investment Company Institute, a mutal fund industry group,
opposes portfolio manager disclosure, claiming it would be an
additional burden for the funds and create a ``superstar'' system
of fund managers.
   ``We did not agree with the fund manager disclosure, which
places undue emphasis on the cult of personality. It ignores the
actual basis on which funds hire advisers,'' said Betty K. Hart, a
spokeswoman for the trade group.
   ``In 1972, 1982 and 1984 this issue has come up and we have
always opposed it. We still oppose it. There are some very
succesful funds that run by committee,'' she added.
   Ms. Hart said the ICI was willing to go along with the
disclosure rule in just two instances: ``where a fund promotes an
individual to the press and the investment public, or if the
individual is of such critical importance to the advisory
organization that it would cease to exist in the same manner if
they left.''
   The two other proposals are less controversial. To simply
information in a mutual fund's prospectus, the SEC staff suggested
shortening tables listing a fund's total return per share.
   To provide investors with more information to easily evaluate a
fund, the staff proposed following one of two alternatives: A
fund's managers would be required either to discuss and analyze its
fiscal year performance in relation to its investment objectives or
compare its total returns over one-, five- and 10-year periods to
the performance of a securities index.
   The commission, which regulates investment companies as well as
the securities industry, voted to submit the proposed rules for a
60-day public comment period.
   Following that period, Ms. McGrath said her staff will review
comments _ both pro and con _ make any changes deemed necessary and
submit the proposed rule changes to the commissioners ``and they
will vote it up or down.''
   She said the staff hoped to submit the proposals to the
commission by late spring or early summer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891222-0235 </DOCNO>
