<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed in Quiet Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices rose slightly today amid
news of new export business while other grain and soybean futures
were unchanged to lower in early trading on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   The Agriculture Department announced this morning it had
accepted two bids from exporters to cover sales of nearly 110,000
metric tons of U.S. wheat to Iraq at subsidized prices.
   The corn, oat and soybean markets were nearly unchanged in
extremely quiet trading with many traders absent because of the
sub-zero weather in Chicago or because of the upcoming holiday
weekend.
   ``I really don't know when I've ever seen it this slow,'' said
John Frazier, an executive vice president of Balfour Maclaine Corp.
on the trading floor.
   The markets were scheduled to close at noon central time and
will not reopen until Tuesday.
   In early trading, wheat futures were } cent to 1\ cents higher
with the contract for delivery in March at $4.14 a bushel; corn
futures were unchanged to \ cent lower with March at $2.38{ a
bushel; oats were unchanged to \ cent lower with March at $1.54\ a
bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 2 cents lower with January at
$5.73{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were narrowly mixed in quiet trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .02 cent to .15 cent lower with February at
76.70 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .18 cent
higher with January at 84.70 cents a pound; live hogs were .42 cent
lower to .15 cent higher with February at 49.05 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .02 cent lower to .48 cent higher with
February at 50 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled higher on Thursday.
