<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-89 1800EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-FedPolicy     12-22 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fed Policy,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Remained Open To Lower Interest Rates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve policy makers decided not to
change monetary policy at their late fall meeting but left open the
possibility of lower interest rates if economic events dictated,
according to minutes released Friday.
   ``While current indicators of economic activity suggested a
somewhat weaker expansion, most of the members agreed that a steady
policy course was desirable at this point, especially in light of
the stimulus provided by recent easing actions,'' said the minutes
of the Nov. 14 meeting of the Federal Open Market Committee.
   Most of the policy makers agreed, however, ``some further easing
might be needed if the incoming information on business activity
suggested more softening than most members currently expected.''
   The Fed permitted short-term interest rates to drop a quarter of
a percentage point earlier this week to 8.25 percent. It was the
first decrease since Nov. 7 when the central bank also permitted
the federal funds rate to decline a quarter of a percentage point.
   Manipulation of this rate, the interest rate that banks charge
each other for overnight loans, is the primary lever the Fed uses
to control short-term interest rates. It has used this lever
several times since last June, when it began relaxing its grip on
credit to slow inflation.
   The initial decision to keep policy unchanged was reached on a
10-1 vote of the open market committee, composed of Fed governors
in Washington and five of the 12 Fed regional bank presidents.
   Gov. Martha Seeger cast the dissenting vote, contending a
further easing was needed in view of persisting weakness in the
manufacturing sector, particularly automobiles, and a likely
softening in construction and capital expenditures.
   The committee met again Monday and Tuesday, but minutes of that
meeting will not be released until next month. The committee
gathers in secret eight times a year to formulate monetary policy
and confers by telephone as needed.
   In its review of economic conditions last month, it found that
the economy continued to expand, ``though unevenly and at a
somewhat slower pace than earlier in the year.
   ``While the service-producing sector appeared to be growing
moderately, manufacturing had been weak, owing to sluggish demand
and to strikes and other disruptions to production,'' the minutes
said. ``Price increases had been smaller since midyear, but there
had been no abatement of wage inflation.''
   Non-farm employment grew appreciably in October, it said, but
slower than in previous months.
   ``Widespread job gains were apparent in the service-producing
sector, but manufacturing payrolls declined further as a result of
continued weakness in motor vehicles and other durable goods
industries,'' the report said.
   The minutes also showed the Fed staff expected the economy was
likely to grow at a slower pace over the next several quarters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891222-0283 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-89 1808EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Columbia-MovieAds     12-22 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Columbia-Movie Ads,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Columbia Pictures Moves Tri-Star Pictures Ad Account to McCann-Erickson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Columbia Pictures Entertainment Inc. said Friday
that it had decided to put McCann-Erickson Worldwide in charge of
placing domestic advertising for both its Columbia Pictures and
Tri-Star Pictures movies.
   The decision could mean an extra $70 million to $75 million in
annual billings for the giant New York-based agency, which had
previously held the assignment only for Columbia Pictures ads.
   The loser is AC&amp;R Advertising, a unit of Saatchi &amp; Saatchi Co.
PLC, which had been responsible for placing the Tri-State Pictures
advertising.
   Among Tri-Star's recent films have been ``Steel Magnolias'' and
``Look Who's Talking,'' while Columbia's recent films have included
``When Harry Met Sally ...'' and ``Ghostbusters II.''
   Calls were placed to both agencies, but went unanswered Friday
afternoon. Many businesses closed early Friday in advance of the
three-day Christmas holiday weekend.
   The move comes a month after Columbia Pictures Entertainment was
acquired by Japan's Sony Corp. in a $3.4 billion buyout, but a
Columbia spokesman who asked not to be identified said the decision
was unrelated to the buyout.
   The Columbia and Tri-Star studios merged their marketing
departments last March and had reportedly been reviewing ad agency
assignments for several months.
   In response to inquiries, the Columbia Pictures spokesman in
Burbank, Calif., said the decision to consolidate North American
media placement for the two studios was the next step in the merger
of the marketing departments.
   The spokesman declined to disclose how much the studios spend on
advertising their films.
   But industry sources said that annual spending came to between
$140 million and $150 million this year evenly divided between the
two studios.
   McCann-Erickson, whose total U.S. billings amounted to $1.3
billion in 1988, has handled media placement for Columbia Pictures
for about two years.
   Among its other clients are Coca-Cola Co.'s soft drinks, General
Motors Corp.'s Buick division, American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.'s
business-to-business advertising and Exxon Corp.'s gasoline and
motor oil products.
   It recently won a $25 million assignment for Taster's Choice
coffee from Nestle, a $25 million job for unspecified new products
from RJR Nabisco and a $10 million account for Fidelity Investments.
   AC&amp;R Advertising had U.S. billings of $355.6 million in 1988.
Its clients include Austin Rover of North America, Fosters Lager
Beer and Regency Cruises.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
