<FIRST>u f BC-BusinessHighlights     12-22 0848</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0889</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for durable goods
posted a 5.1 percent gain in November, the sharpest increase in a
year, the government said. Analysts said the report suggested the
economy can avoid a recession.
   The Commerce Department said Friday that orders for durable
goods _ costly items expected to last at least three years _
increased to a seasonally adjusted $130.7 billion last month after
dropping 0.7 percent in October and 1.2 percent in September.
   The gain in orders was spread through all categories and was the
largest since a 7.4 percent jump last December. It averted the
first three-month decline since 1986.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Ethics Committee said it will
formally investigate five senators who intervened with banking
regulators on behalf of a wealthy contributor whose huge savings
and loan was failing.
